image.caption:
🦘Gli aborigeni della Tasmania raccontano che la creazione avvenne grazie a due spiriti fratelli chiamati Moinee e Droemerdene. Il primo era talvolta raffigurato come una formica, e diede forma al mondo, creando anche il primo canguro, un essere ancestrale di grande importanza. 

🦘 Droemerdene se ne stava in alto, nella stella Canopo, e osservava perplesso l’opera del fratello. Vedeva i canguri correre e saltare, e non gli sembravano ancora perfetti. 

🦘 Decise di migliorarne alcuni, perciò tolse a qualche esemplare la coda, piegò le articolazioni delle loro gambe nel senso opposto, e insegnò loro a sedere attorno a un fuoco per riscaldarsi, a cuocere il cibo e a cacciare. 

🦘 Dal primo canguro, Droemerdene creò Parlevar, il primo essere umano. Moinee non apprezzò quella modifica alla sua creatura, e i due fratelli iniziarono a litigare. Ben presto la discussione si tramutò in un vero e proprio scontro, facendo rimbombare i cieli di grida e colpi. 

🦘 Dopo una strenua lotta, Moinee cadde dal cielo, schiantandosi sulla terra e diventando una delle rocce di Coxes Bight. Anche suo fratello perse l’equilibrio, e finì in mare, nei pressi di Louisa Bay. 

🦘 Colui che, seppur involontariamente, aveva dato origine allo scontro, Parlevar, il primo essere umano, continuò a vivere sulla terra, tenendo in grande considerazione il canguro, che in fondo era il suo antenato.

image.caption:
Cake upgrade… because why not.
🖤💛❤️

Today is “Australia Day”. 
A strange day in Australia. It’s pretty obvious that the date needs to change for such a “celebration”. 
I urge you to use today to learn about your local land, your local mob, and listen. 
I am very fortunate to live on Gubbi Gubbi land, what I consider the most beautiful of all the lands. Over the last two years I have done a lot of research around my local area, and it is bloody shocking to say the least. The fact there is a road around the corner from where I live called “Murdering Creek Road” is enough to make my skin crawl! 
How ever you choose to spend your day, be mindful, be kind, and don’t be like scomo 🖤💛❤️#alwayswasalwayswillbe

image.alt_text: Photo by PaleoAnalysis YouTube Channel on February 06, 2022. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'PROCOPTODON PROCOPTODON GIANT SHORT FACED KANGAROO'.
image.caption:
Procoptodon is an extinct genus of giant short-faced (sthenurine) kangaroos that lived in Australia during the Pleistocene Epoch. P. goliah, the largest known kangaroo species that ever existed, stood at about 2 m (6.6 ft). They weighed about 200–240 kg (440–530 lb). Other members of the genus were smaller, however; Procoptodon gilli was the smallest of all of the sthenurine kangaroos, standing approximately 1 m (3 ft 3 in) tall.
.
P. goliah was mainly known for living in semiarid areas of South Australia and New South Wales. These environments were harsh, characterised by vast areas of treeless, wind-blown sand dunes. However, the area around Lake Menindee, in western New South Wales, had a cooler, wetter climate at the time Procoptodon existed. The surrounding area was a mosaic of sclerophyll forest, woodland, savannah, and plains, but sand dunes would have also formed along the edges of the Menindee. Fossilized footprints have also been found on Kangaroo Island.
.
P. goliah was unable to hop as a mode of transportation, and would have been unable to accelerate sufficiently due to its weight. Broad hips and ankle joints, adapted to resist torsion or twisting, point to an upright posture where weight is supported by one leg at a time. Its broad hips also allowed for another important modification – large buttocks – a feature shared with other walking species.
.

image.alt_text: Photo by Frontier War Stories on January 29, 2022. May be an image of one or more people.
image.caption:
The Queensland Native Mounted Police was organised along paramilitary lines, consisting of detachments of Aboriginal troopers led by white officers. It covered the whole of Queensland, including 170 camps, and was explicitly constituted to protect the lives, livelihoods and property of settlers and to prevent (and punish) any Aboriginal aggression or resistance.
This was often accomplished through violence in many forms, leading Australian historian Henry Reynolds to characterise the NMP as “the most violent organisation in Australian history”.

image.alt_text: A tall and teetering stack of books all by First Nations authors. On top of the stack is a small Aboriginal flag made out of soap
image.caption:
📚 every year I make this stack and every year it gets bigger and bigger and every year I feel so proud and excited to have the opportunity to read more and more books by First Nations authors, about First Nations characters and First Nations cultures and Countries 

🖤Yes, these are all the books by First Nations Australian authors I own. And there are so many more, I am pleased to say, that I have read and do not own and more still that I have yet to buy and read myself. I will never run out of books by people who look like me, think like me, talk like me, feel like me. Something that a ten-year younger version of myself, the one whose only fictional encountering of Indigenous peoples - and all people of colour as a matter of fact - were caricatured by White people, would have marvelled at. 

I have always been a reader. I have always imagined myself into fictional settings. I have always been so grateful for the books I read and the authors that write them. But I didn’t know what I was missing, because I didn’t think it would ever be possible to read a character as Blak, not as wishful thinking but as canon. I wish younger me could have had what I had now. I know they would have felt so much less alone, less insecure, afraid to identify, armoured against the hate and bigotry. But now I have access to First Nations books, and a place to shout and celebrate them and hopefully, like my stack grows every year, no Blak kids will ever have to feel like they will never see themselves in the fiction they read. We all belong in the literary world. As writers, readers and reviewers.👐🏾✨

to mob, I am sending you strength for the next couple of days in particular 💪🏾
to non-Indigenous folks, thank you for uplifting our voices and joining our fight

image.alt_text: Photo by George Eastman Museum on January 26, 2022. May be a black-and-white image.
image.caption:
"The phrase “untouched landscape” refers to the idea of terra nullius, which was what the British constituted colonizing Australia and taking the land off Aboriginal people. So terra nullius means “no man’s land.” So the idea was that the British didn’t recognize that Aboriginal land ownership or Aboriginal land use was the same as Western cultivation or Western ideas of land ownership." -James Tylor

See his work on view now in From an Untouched Landscape at the museum. Learn more at eastman.org/Tylor. 

James Tylor (Kaurna, Māori, and Australian, b. 1986), (Vanished Scenes) From an Untouched Landscape 2, 2018. Inkjet print on Hahnemuhle paper with hole removed to a black velvet void, 9 13/16 × 9 13/16 in. (25 × 25 cm). Lent by Vivien Anderson Gallery. © James Tylor

Your courage and determination has been a valuable lesson to so many including myself.  Keep it up my girl. 
The sky is definitely the limit and don’t let anything or anyone say otherwise. 
I love you my baby girl. @freodockersaflw @mikaylamorrisonnn #fremantledockerswomens #aflw #aboriginal #prouddad #debutante

May be an image of text that says 'Anton Schirripa @YourUncleAnton Hey #ChangeTheDate folks just wondering which particular date you'd choose for us to celebrate a colony that continues to exist illegally on stolen land; it's history of genocide; and it's ongoing colonisation of Black bodies and lands?'.
image.caption:
There's no pride in genocide, but that's precisely what January 26 represents: the beginning of the genocide of Indigenous peoples across the unceded, stolen lands now commonly known as Australia. 

It's beyond time to stop celebrating the date upon which we mark the arrival of a murderous invasion. 

What is there to celebrate about the massacre of First Nations peoples? 

Where is the pride in the astronomical rates of Indigenous youth suicide? 

How are we we to rejoice in the epidemic of Blak deaths in custody? 

What is to be commemorated in white supremacist police forces? 

How does one boast about the systemic erasure of the world's oldest continuing culture? 

If January 26 is to be marked in any way, let that mark be a stain of shame. 

Let it be a date upon which those of us who benefit from this violence make reparations with our wallets. 

Today I am donating to @dhadjowa_foundation, a charity which provides culturally safe support to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people whose loved ones have died in custody. 

I suggest you do the same, or find another Indigenous charity to support. 

(And if you do, please tag them in the comments here so we can all check them out. Thanks!)

image.alt_text: Photo by Diego Bonetto on February 05, 2022. May be an image of food.
image.caption:
Bunya bunya kernels. 

These incredible and ancient tree’s nuts have been the gathering call for Aboriginal Australians for thousands of years. 

The generous tree drops a bumper crop of ‘pine nuts’ every 3-5 years and when that happened Aboriginal groups from all over Eastern Australia would gather at the Bunya Mountains near Brisbane, Queensland. 

During these corroborees (gathering) disputes were settled, marriages were arranged and goods were traded. 
.
This year is a bumper year and you can find the nuts all over Australia as the trees have been planted as far south as Tasmania and west as Perth. 
.
When engaging with these ancient foods think at what it provided for thousands of people before you. 
Nature is generous. 
.

image.alt_text: Photo by By Lauren Clara 🌈🖤💛♥️ in Yuin Country with @angiefarrugia. May be an image of outdoors.
image.caption:
I had the absolute honour of creating this artwork for Oranges Toolkit. Oranges Toolkit boosts organisational and individual performance through wellbeing and resilience training programs. 

Oranges Toolkit was born out of Camp Quality which holds a special place in my heart. 

It was also an honour and full circle moment to have the wonderful @angiefarrugia ask me to do this (she was my first ever commission!)

“This artwork represents The Oranges Toolkit and the connection that this organisation has as a community. This artwork represents not only the work community of The Oranges Toolkit but also the impact it has on the wider community.

In the middle of the artwork is a yarning circle, representing The Oranges Toolkit team. The yarning circles at the bottom and top of the artwork represent the different organisations, offices, and employees across this country.

The colours reflect the branding of The Oranges Toolkit. The kangaroo tracks on the side of the artwork represent the travel done and the travel between different communities and countries.

The connected watering holes at each corner of the middle yarning circle represent the flow on effect that the organisation has with the wider community.

The smaller yarning circles are scattered throughout the whole artwork to represent and show the different communities across this country that will encounter and be impacted by The Oranges Toolkit.”

image.alt_text: Photo by Yarn Marketplace on January 25, 2022. May be an image of one or more people, people standing, outdoors and text that says 'CHANGE THE DATE ALAIS'.
image.caption:
January 26th isn’t and should never have been a day for celebration. 🖤💛❤️💚💙 It is a day that marks the invasion of the British, and the beginning of the desecration of First Nations culture and lives through genocide and dispossession. 
.
For decades Indigenous peoples and allies have been boycotting Australia Day, fighting for it to be renamed, and for our national day's date to be changed. On January the 26th in 1938, First Nations people protested against Australia Day and named it a 'Day of Mourning'. On this day in 1972, the Aboriginal Tent Embassy was established outside of Parliament House. Today, protests continue to take place each year, and we encourage everyone to support changing or abolishing the date. 
.
If you would like to learn more about the history and how to support First Nations communities on Invasion Day, there are so many incredible articles and resources by Indigenous people you can check out, as well as non-for-profits you can support: 
.
✊ @childrensground - is a non-for-profit who supports Indigenous children’s education and wellbeing. They offer an excellent list of books to read, movies to watch and non-for-profit organisations to support.
.
✊ @commongroundaustralia - is a non-for-profit that focuses on bringing about change within education and justice systems for First Nations peoples. They have an excellent article on their blog that talks about some of the history of Invasion Day, and gives Indigenous perspectives on what the day means.
.
✊ How To Be A Better Ally - Kaytetye woman and CEO of Common Ground, Rona Glynn-McDonald talked to Refinery 29 about how to be a better ally on Invasion Day. In the interview, she gives insight into the significance of January 26, and the importance of amplifying First Nations voices. You can find the full article via their page @refinery29au.
.
✊ Protests - Russh Magazine has written an article with a comprehensive list of where you can protest this Invasion Day. Remember to stay safe and adhere to covid safe precautions when attending. You can find their full list as well as non-for-profits to support via their link in bio @russhmagazine.

image.alt_text: Photo by Joseph Tawadros on January 24, 2022. May be an image of child, sitting, standing, outdoors and text that says 'BRANg REDFERN PUBLIC SCHOOL 990 YEAR LM'.
image.caption:
I went to Redfern Public School. A place which wasn’t the highest on the social economic ladder but one of incredible soul, and looking back at those days, I now see how important it was to shape my understanding of Australia. It was a real tight knit community, with indigenous Aunts, Uncles and Elders, who visited regularly to help out at the school and offer support to those who were 
disadvantaged. 

The school was a mixture of Indigenous children, refugees, as well as new immigrants like myself. We played Rugby League together, handball, danced together and took part in indigenous ceremonies. We learnt how to make damper and one year cooked a kangaroo under the ground of the school oval. 

Australia has an indigenous people, with their own traditions, customs, ceremonies, laws, foods and culture. Going to Redfern public school taught me this and it was something that I took for granted at the time, but something I’m glad I lived so I can understand the feelings of my indigenous brothers and sisters now. As Australia Day approaches, It is easy to flippantly dismiss changing the date, and I fear I might’ve been one of those people had I not gone to that school, but I think it’s important to educate people, teach about the atrocities committed by the British, change the date (or sentiment) and create a celebration which is inclusive of everyone.

I love Australia and loved growing up in such a diverse multicultural society which shaped my music and the way I view the world. I’ve been thankful for the opportunities that me and my family were given when we first arrived in 1986. 

Redfern Public School was never big on school uniform 😊 which one am I? 😎

image.caption:
🇬🇧Shining a light on the creativity and strength of First Nations people is of vital importance to us and our national identity. Indigenous Australia is the true foundation of our multicultural society and as the children of Italian immigrants we are eternally grateful. It’s a huge honour to collaborate with pre-eminent Aboriginal photographer, Wayne Quilliam to capture this collection for J’Aton Couture and Kmpiumini. He is one of Australia’s leading creators and dedicated to exploring the nuances of Indigenous thinking and identity in contemporary culture.


🇮🇹Far luce sulla creatività e la forza del popolo dei nativi d'Australia è di vitale importanza per noi e per la nostra identità nazionale. 
L'Australia indigena è il vero fondamento della nostra società multiculturale e come figli di immigrati italiani ne siamo eternamente grati. 
È un grande onore collaborare con il preminente fotografo aborigeno Wayne Quilliam per dare vita a questa collezione "J’Aton Couture e Kmpiumini". 
Wayne Qulliam è uno dei principali creatori australiani e si dedica all'esplorazione delle sfumature del pensiero e delle identità indigene nella cultura contemporanea.

Bunya bunya kernels. 

These incredible and ancient tree’s nuts have been the gathering call for Aboriginal Australians for thousands of years. 

The generous tree drops a bumper crop of ‘pine nuts’ every 3-5 years and when that happened Aboriginal groups from all over Eastern Australia would gather at the Bunya Mountains near Brisbane, Queensland. 

During these corroborees (gathering) disputes were settled, marriages were arranged and goods were traded. 
.
This year is a bumper year and you can find the nuts all over Australia as the trees have been planted as far south as Tasmania and west as Perth. 
.
When engaging with these ancient foods think at what it provided for thousands of people before you. 
Nature is generous. 
.
